<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-048-156 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 343 699</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Sources  Oct 1991 v2 n10 p383(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Axonix DataFile: no-fault data to go. (portable hard drive)(Hardware Review) (Durability Tests) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lockwood, Russ.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The $399 20Mbyte DataFile portable hard disk drive from AxonixCorp is extremely useful for transferring data from one computerto another without using floppy disks.andP;  It can also be used as aprimary or secondary hard drive for laptop or desktop computers.andO;It connects to the system through the parallel port and hasautomatic install software.andP;  The DataFile is remarkably sturdy andnever failed in three months of normal office use including movingit, piling things on it and now and then hitting it.andP;  The case iswell engineered to protect the hard disk.andP;  Axonix plans onreleasing battery-powered versions of the DataFile in 2.5-inch40Mbyte- and 60Mbyte versions under the series name DataFile LT.andO;The price for the 20Mbyte system is down from $499 to $399 inthree months.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Axonix Corp. (Products).andO;Product:   Axonix DataFile (Removable hard disk drive) (evaluation).andO;Topic:     EvaluationHard DiskRemovable DiskDisk Drives.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   Product summary. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Axonix Corp., 1214 Wilmington Ave., Salt Lake City, UT 84106 SalesInformation:  800-866-9797, 8 a.m.andP;  to 5 p.m.andP;  weekdays (Mountain time)Mail-Order Price:  $399andM;Once again, I loaded 10MB of programs and data onto the 60MB hard drive of abrand-new notebook computer without touching a single floppy disk.andP;  And I didit in a fraction of the time it would take to swap floppies in and out of theA drive.andP;  DataFile, a 20MB portable hard drive from Axonix Corp., is the keyto this efficiency.andM;Hooking up the DataFile to a new laptop or desktop takes all of five minutes:It attaches to your system's parallel port and includes an automatic installprogram.andP;  The installation procedure is slick and smooth, though I've had tomodify the CONFIG.SYS file on some systems to include the LASTDRIVE DOScommand.andP;  Still, that's a small inconvenience for such portability.andM;I ran programs from the DataFile, used COPY to transfer subdirectories backand forth, and in general, treated it as just another drive on the system.andO;As time passed, I used it more for data transportation than as a primary orsecondary hard drive for laptops or desktops.andP;  According to David Cox, vicepresident of marketing for Axonix, customer feedback shows I'm not the onlyperson using the DataFile in this way.andM;After three months of use, the DataFile still performs flawlessly.andP;  Undernormal office conditions--moving it around, piling things on top of it, andthe occasional jolt--it never even hiccuped.andP;  I'm more than satisfied withthe durability and reliability of the DataFile's case, which does a great jobof protecting its Conner hard drive.andM;I've never left the DataFile plugged into the parallel port for long, since Ineed the port for printing on desktop systems.andP;  On laptops, the DataFile'slack of battery power precludes using it away from a power outlet.andP;  By theend of 1991, however, Axonix will release both 40MB and 60MB battery-poweredversions--tentatively dubbed the DataFile LT series, based on 2.5-inch harddrives.andM;Since I reviewed the DataFile, the 20MB unit's price dropped from $459 to$399.andP;  The price for the 40MB model remains unchanged at $699, but the 100MBversion dropped from $1,199 to $999 and the 200MB version dropped from $1,899to $1,499.andM;If you're looking for a way to zip programs and data from one computer toanother, take a long look at the Axonix DataFile.andP;  I did, and I came awayimpressed.andO;</TEXT></DOC>